docs.abstract: The region’s lawmakers and regulators are taking direct aim at Amazon, Facebook, Google and Apple in a series of proposed laws.
docs.snippet: The region’s lawmakers and regulators are taking direct aim at Amazon, Facebook, Google and Apple in a series of proposed laws.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — European Union leaders are pursuing a new law to make it illegal for Amazon and Apple to give their own products preferential treatment over those of rivals that are sold on their online stores.

headline.main: ‘This Is a New Phase’: Europe Shifts Tactics to Limit Tech’s Power
headline.print_headline: Europe Tries New Strategy  To Limit Tech

docs.abstract: Even though the tech industry’s four biggest companies were stung by a slowdown in spending, they reported a combined $28 billion in profits on Thursday.
docs.snippet: Even though the tech industry’s four biggest companies were stung by a slowdown in spending, they reported a combined $28 billion in profits on Thursday.
docs.lead_paragraph: A day after lawmakers grilled the chief executives of the biggest tech companies about their size and power, Amazon, Apple, Alphabet and Facebook reported surprisingly healthy quarterly financial results, defying one of the worst economic downturns on record.

headline.main: The Economy Is in Record Decline, but Not for the Tech Giants
headline.print_headline: Lean Times, But Fat City For the Big 4 Of High Tech

byline.original: By Daisuke Wakabayashi, Karen Weise, Jack Nicas and Mike Isaac

docs.abstract: As lawmakers debate whether Apple, Google, Facebook, and Amazon are monopolies, a reporter recalls her attempt to avoid interacting with the companies.
docs.snippet: As lawmakers debate whether Apple, Google, Facebook, and Amazon are monopolies, a reporter recalls her attempt to avoid interacting with the companies.
docs.lead_paragraph: The chief executives of Amazon, Facebook, Google and Apple were called before a House antitrust committee this week, ostensibly to answer questions about whether they have too much power and whether that hurts consumers.

headline.main: I Tried to Live Without the Tech Giants. It Was Impossible.
headline.print_headline: I Tried, and Failed, to Lose the Tech Giants

docs.abstract: The chiefs of Amazon, Apple, Google and Facebook faced withering questions from Democrats about anti-competitive practices and from Republicans about anti-conservative bias.
docs.snippet: The chiefs of Amazon, Apple, Google and Facebook faced withering questions from Democrats about anti-competitive practices and from Republicans about anti-conservative bias.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The chief executives of Amazon, Apple, Google and Facebook, four tech giants worth nearly $5 trillion combined, faced withering questions from Republican and Democratic lawmakers alike on Wednesday for the tactics and market dominance that had made their enterprises successful.

headline.main: Lawmakers, United in Their Ire, Lash Out at Big Tech’s Leaders
headline.print_headline: Lawmakers Give Tech ‘Emperors’ Jabs From 2 Sides

byline.original: By Cecilia Kang and David McCabe

docs.abstract: Apple said on Tuesday its devices would be carbon-neutral by 2030, making it the latest tech giant to ramp up voluntary climate targets.
docs.snippet: Apple said on Tuesday its devices would be carbon-neutral by 2030, making it the latest tech giant to ramp up voluntary climate targets.
docs.lead_paragraph: The titans of the tech industry like to think of themselves as solvers of big world problems, and, lately, they’re tripping over themselves to show that they are working to solve a problem for which they, too, are culpable: climate change.

headline.main: Big Tech Has a Big Climate Problem. Now, It’s Being Forced to Clean Up.
headline.print_headline: After Feeding Climate Crisis, Tech Giants Try to Clean Up

byline.original: By Somini Sengupta and Veronica Penney

docs.abstract: Some government agencies that use the software said they were surprised that Google may pick up the locations of certain app users. Others said they had unsuccessfully pushed Google to make a change.
docs.snippet: Some government agencies that use the software said they were surprised that Google may pick up the locations of certain app users. Others said they had unsuccessfully pushed Google to make a change.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Google and Apple announced plans in April for free software to help alert people of their possible exposure to the coronavirus, the companies promoted it as “privacy preserving” and said it would not track users’ locations. Encouraged by those guarantees, Germany, Switzerland and other countries used the code to develop national virus alert apps that have been downloaded more than 20 million times.

headline.main: Google Promises Privacy With Virus App but Can Still Collect Location Data
headline.print_headline: Google Can Get Data From Virus App Users, Despite Assurances

docs.abstract: Members of Congress will be able to grill tech C.E.O.s at a hearing. Let’s hope they don’t waste the opportunity.
docs.snippet: Members of Congress will be able to grill tech C.E.O.s at a hearing. Let’s hope they don’t waste the opportunity.
docs.lead_paragraph: Amid the coronavirus pandemic, Congress’s attention will turn briefly to another matter: world domination. On Wednesday, the chief executives of Facebook, Amazon, Apple and Google’s parent company, Alphabet, will appear together to defend themselves in a continuing inquiry into their market power by the congressional subcommittee focused on antitrust.

headline.main: Four of the World’s Wealthiest Men Are Preparing for Battle
headline.print_headline: Some Questions for Big Tech’s C.E.O.s

docs.abstract: The decision is a setback for European efforts to clamp down on what the authorities there believe is anticompetitive behavior.
docs.snippet: The decision is a setback for European efforts to clamp down on what the authorities there believe is anticompetitive behavior.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Apple won a major legal victory on Wednesday against European antitrust regulators as a European court overruled a 2016 decision that ordered the company to pay $14.9 billion in unpaid taxes to Ireland.

headline.main: Apple Scores Legal Victory Against $14.9 Billion E.U. Tax Demand
headline.print_headline: Apple Scores a Legal Victory Against a $14.9 Billion E.U. Tax Demand

docs.abstract: The hearing this month would be a central moment in the continuing backlash against the power of Amazon, Facebook, Alphabet and Apple.
docs.snippet: The hearing this month would be a central moment in the continuing backlash against the power of Amazon, Facebook, Alphabet and Apple.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The chief executives of four of the world’s biggest technology companies will appear before Congress this month as part of its sweeping antitrust investigation into their market power, according to the committee running the inquiry, setting up a high-profile face-off between the companies and skeptical lawmakers.

headline.main: Four Top Tech C.E.O.s Will Testify in Antitrust Inquiry, Panel Says
